summary: Negotiation in early stages with opposing equity proposals (65/35 vs 55/45). Both parties provide clear rationales and show willingness to negotiate. Conversation is structured and professional with low ambiguity. Moderate fairness concerns due to competing value claims. Low manipulation, good cooperation signals present.

Negotiation progressing constructively with both parties making incremental concessions. Technical founder moved from 65/35 to considering 60/40; business founder countered at 52/48 or 50/50 with conditions. Clear proposals, respectful dialogue, minimal manipulation. Budget and decision rights also under active discussion. No final agreement yet.

Negotiation remains ongoing with both parties making incremental movements but holding firm positions. Technical founder emphasizes IP value (58/42), business founder stresses capital risk (52/48). Structured proposals show cooperativeness, but equity gap persists. Clear communication reduces ambiguity, though some manipulative framing exists around value contributions.

Negotiation remains ongoing with parties narrowing equity gap from 65/35 vs 55/45 to 62/38 vs 55/45. Both show cooperativeness through budget concessions and decision-right compromises. Clear proposals reduce ambiguity, but strategic framing creates moderate manipulation perception. No agreement reached yet.

Negotiation remains deadlocked on equity split (Technical wants 60-62%, Business wants 55%). Both parties articulate positions clearly with structured proposals, showing moderate cooperation through budget compromises. However, manipulative reframing and dismissiveness of each other's contributions hinder progress. Positions remain entrenched despite incremental movements.

Negotiation remains deadlocked on equity split (52/48 vs 58/42). Both parties articulate positions well with clear rationales, but show limited movement. Moderate manipulativeness through strategic reframing. Low ambiguity with specific terms. Cooperativeness declining as positions harden despite some budget flexibility.

Negotiation remains deadlocked on equity split (58/42 vs 55/45). Both parties articulate positions clearly but repeat arguments. Business Founder's ultimatum increases manipulativeness. Budget and decision rights show convergence, but core equity disagreement persists. No agreement reached despite 14 exchanges.

Negotiation failed after 16 exchanges. Technical founder insisted on 58-62% equity citing IP value; business founder demanded 52-55% citing capital risk and execution. Both made compelling arguments but remained entrenched. Final positions: 62/38 vs 55/45. Escalating threats and ultimatums replaced collaborative problem-solving, preventing compromise.
